Your options to resume:
Option 1 — Manual Resume Command (simplest)
When it stops, just type this in the same chat:
Resume from where you stopped. 
Read target/site/jacoco/jacoco.csv to check current coverage. 
Continue the loop for all classes still below 90%. 
Do NOT restart from scratch.
It will read the existing coverage report and continue from where it left off.

Option 2 — Add a Resume Trigger to the prompt
Add this block at the very bottom of your system prompt:
## RESUME PROTOCOL

If you are starting a conversation where tests already exist:
  Step 1: FIRST run <<MVN_PATH>> clean test jacoco:report
  Step 2: Read target/site/jacoco/jacoco.csv
  Step 3: Calculate current coverage per class
  Step 4: Build UNCOVERED_CLASSES list from CSV
  Step 5: Skip classes already at 90%+
  Step 6: Continue MASTER EXECUTION LOOP from LOOP_START
          for remaining uncovered classes only
  
DO NOT regenerate tests for classes already at 90%+.
DO NOT start from scratch if test files already exist.
ALWAYS check jacoco.csv first before doing anything.
Then when it stops, start a new chat, switch to the mode, and type:
Resume test coverage improvement. 
Check jacoco.csv and continue for classes below 90%.

Option 3 — Break it into smaller chunks (most reliable)
Instead of running the whole project at once, tell it to work package by package:
Focus only on: src/main/java/com/example/service/
Generate tests, compile, and reach 90% for this 
package only. Then stop and report.
Then next run:
Focus only on: src/main/java/com/example/controller/
This prevents context overflow and gives you predictable progress.

Recommended approach:
Phase 1 chat -> run on /service package
Phase 2 chat -> run on /controller package  
Phase 3 chat -> run on /repository package
Phase 4 chat -> run on /util package
Final chat   -> run full project to verify overall 90%
